50|$|The first Maltese <b>euro</b> <b>coins</b> were {{available}} for the public on 1 December 2007, as business starter packs worth €131 each started being available for small businesses to fill up their cash registers with sufficient amount <b>of</b> <b>euro</b> <b>coins</b> before the €-day. Mini-kits each worth €11.65 {{were available}} {{for the general public}} on 10 December 2007. Malta issued 33,000 business starter kits and 330,000 starter kits for the general public. All the 33,000 starter kits for businesses were sold.|$|R
5000|$|Hungarian <b>euro</b> <b>coins</b> {{have not}} yet been designed. When asked about the {{production}} <b>of</b> the <b>euro</b> <b>coins</b> in a 2010 interview appearing in Coin News magazine in the UK, Ferenc Gaál, Mintmaster replied: [...] "Originally, we were supposed to have finished production of forint coinage in 2008. This project (the facilities of the new mint premises) was specifically planned to meet the requirements <b>of</b> the new <b>euro</b> currency which will be launched in Hungary in the future, this new facility will ensure a very smooth change-over which will also provide us with the latest technology for minting & production <b>of</b> <b>euro</b> <b>coins.</b> It will take us only six months to produce enough coins to change from forints to euros. All the conditions are in place for a hopefully smooth change-over. Now, we're just waiting for the 'go-ahead'!" ...|$|R
